24:04.361 --> 24:07.094
[singing in foreign language]

24:17.895 --> 24:20.826
[indistinct chatter]

24:37.928 --> 24:40.860
[singing continues]

24:55.161 --> 24:56.325
Hello, Jerry.

24:56.327 --> 24:59.623
Moe, nice to see you.
Been a long time.

24:59.625 --> 25:00.926
I was hoping you'd be here.

25:00.928 --> 25:02.758
Oh, yeah? Why?

25:02.760 --> 25:05.027
I understand you're working
in Washington.

25:06.526 --> 25:08.224
Where'd you hear that?

25:08.226 --> 25:10.826
One of the guys.
I can't remember who.

25:18.394 --> 25:20.994
- State Department?
- Uh, yeah, sort of.

25:22.926 --> 25:24.493
How'd you come to get the job?

25:27.194 --> 25:29.925
There's room for people
with languages.

25:29.927 --> 25:31.325
That's what I figured.

25:33.627 --> 25:36.360
[speaking in foreign language]

26:04.494 --> 26:07.191
- How are your knees?
- What do you mean?

26:07.193 --> 26:10.726
I figure a professional
ballplayer's getting 4F.

26:10.728 --> 26:12.126
Bad hinges.

26:12.993 --> 26:15.427
My knees are as passable
as my Italian.

26:18.294 --> 26:20.125
Have you heard
of Bill Donovan?

26:20.127 --> 26:22.891
Yeah, sure. Yale, football.

26:22.893 --> 26:24.926
Medal of Honor, 1918.

26:24.928 --> 26:26.393
He's my boss.

26:27.959 --> 26:32.024
We're setting up a small adjunct
to the State Department.

26:32.026 --> 26:33.359
Here's the number.

26:37.827 --> 26:40.925
- Give this man a call.
- Thanks.

26:42.592 --> 26:45.325
First time I've seen you
at one of these things.

26:45.327 --> 26:47.991
Well, first time
I've come to one.

26:47.993 --> 26:50.924
<i>Gentlemen, may I have
your attention please?</i>

26:51.826 --> 26:53.158
We are at war.

26:54.193 --> 26:56.525
In light of what lies
before us

26:56.527 --> 26:59.757
<i>the challenges, the sacrifices</i>

26:59.759 --> 27:01.525
<i>the losses.</i>

27:01.527 --> 27:03.658
<i>I ask you,
gentlemen of Princeton</i>

27:03.660 --> 27:07.359
to join us in the singing of the
"Battle Hymn Of The Republic."

27:07.361 --> 27:09.294
[choir humming]

27:12.426 --> 27:17.157
♪ Mine eyes have seen the glory
of the coming of the Lord.. ♪

27:17.159 --> 27:19.422
Sorry for the song choice.

27:19.424 --> 27:20.658
What?

27:20.660 --> 27:23.091
♪ Where the grapes
of wrath are stored ♪

27:23.093 --> 27:24.391
♪ He hath loosed.. ♪

27:24.393 --> 27:26.224
At least it's not
"Onward, Christian Soldiers."

27:26.226 --> 27:29.124
♪ Terrible swift sword.. ♪

27:29.126 --> 27:30.524
That would have been fine too.

27:30.526 --> 27:34.358
♪ Marching on ♪

27:34.360 --> 27:39.557
♪ Glory glory hallelujah ♪

27:39.559 --> 27:41.725
♪ Glory glory ♪

27:41.727 --> 27:45.157
♪ Hallelujah ♪

27:45.159 --> 27:49.758
<i>♪ Glory glory hallelujah ♪</i>

27:49.760 --> 27:55.023
<i>♪ His truth is marching on ♪</i>

27:55.025 --> 27:57.857
<i>♪ I have seen Him
in the watch-fires ♪</i>

27:57.859 --> 28:00.324
<i>♪ Of a hundred
circling camps ♪</i>

28:00.326 --> 28:02.990
<i>♪ They have builded Him
an altar ♪</i>

28:02.992 --> 28:05.589
<i>♪ In the evening
dews and damps ♪</i>

28:05.591 --> 28:08.191
<i>♪ I can read
his righteous sentence ♪</i>

28:08.193 --> 28:10.489
<i>♪ By the dim
and flaring lamps ♪</i>

28:10.491 --> 28:14.657
<i>♪ His day is marching on ♪♪</i>

28:14.659 --> 28:17.591
[projector whirring]

28:34.125 --> 28:37.123
<i>Thank you, gentlemen.</i>

28:37.125 --> 28:39.058
[indistinct chatter]

28:44.424 --> 28:47.591
Interesting film
you brought back, Mr. Berg.

28:47.593 --> 28:49.889
What made you make it?

28:49.891 --> 28:51.823
I happened to be in Japan.

28:51.825 --> 28:54.090
A lot of people
happen to be in Japan.

28:54.092 --> 28:56.456
Not all of them go to the top
of a building in Tokyo

28:56.458 --> 28:58.556
and make home movies of the
harbor and naval shipyards.

28:59.859 --> 29:01.857
I had the opportunity.

29:01.859 --> 29:03.625
It seemed the sensible
thing to do.

29:05.592 --> 29:08.123
How did you know then that
we would be at war with Japan?

29:08.125 --> 29:09.757
"The Journal
Of Oriental Society"

29:09.759 --> 29:10.889
was filled with articles

29:10.891 --> 29:12.324
about going to war with Japan.

29:13.193 --> 29:15.256
You read the "JOS?"

29:15.258 --> 29:19.089
Ah, uh, well, that wasn't
apparent from what I just said?

29:19.091 --> 29:22.089
Yes, yes, I suppose it was.

29:23.991 --> 29:25.789
But no one in the government
or the army

29:25.791 --> 29:26.990
asked you
to make the film?

29:26.992 --> 29:28.156
No.

29:28.158 --> 29:30.289
You did it
as a private citizen?

29:30.291 --> 29:32.022
Yes.

29:32.024 --> 29:33.256
[chuckles]

29:34.492 --> 29:36.760
You're an unusual man,
Mr. Berg.

29:37.858 --> 29:39.155
Yes, so I'm told.

29:39.157 --> 29:40.456
Have a seat.

29:41.825 --> 29:43.723
Not married, no children.

29:45.425 --> 29:47.557
Odd for a man your age, no?

29:49.092 --> 29:50.524
Never occurred to me.

29:51.658 --> 29:54.457
May I ask you
a very personal question?

29:56.792 --> 29:58.125
You may.

29:59.592 --> 30:00.824
Are you queer?

30:04.324 --> 30:06.592
I'm good at keeping secrets.

30:15.057 --> 30:17.456
You're also good
at some other things.

30:17.458 --> 30:20.054
You speak
seven languages fluently

30:20.056 --> 30:21.557
another three or four
to a lesser degree.

30:21.559 --> 30:22.955
In addition,
you're an athlete,

30:22.957 --> 30:25.156
which means you're more than up
to the physical requirements

30:25.158 --> 30:26.455
of the job.

30:26.457 --> 30:27.856
What job?

30:27.858 --> 30:29.290
Any job we might care
to give you

30:29.292 --> 30:31.224
in the event that we
bring you into the fold.

30:33.125 --> 30:35.723
Moe, Jerry Fredericks
speaks very highly of you.

30:35.725 --> 30:38.256
We're looking for people
who can keep secrets

30:38.258 --> 30:39.989
but not from us.

30:39.991 --> 30:43.123
We're fighting a war here.
It's very serious business.

30:44.392 --> 30:46.690
Now, personally,
I don't care who a man fucks

30:46.692 --> 30:48.625
as long as he can help us
win this war.

30:51.191 --> 30:52.589
If it comes down to it

30:52.591 --> 30:54.858
I'm willing to die
for my country.

30:59.923 --> 31:02.322
They say that patriotism

31:02.324 --> 31:04.755
is the last refuge
of a scoundrel.

31:04.757 --> 31:06.988
It isn't they.

31:06.990 --> 31:08.689
It's Samuel Johnson.

31:08.691 --> 31:11.757
And it's not the last,
it's the first.

31:13.825 --> 31:15.823
Welcome to the OSS, Mr. Berg.

31:18.558 --> 31:21.787
<i>There were many new developments
today at home and abroad.</i>

31:21.789 --> 31:25.522
<i>The headlines, Germans claim
victory in the Crimea.</i>

31:25.524 --> 31:28.356
<i>The Russians report gains
around Moscow and Leningrad.</i>

31:28.358 --> 31:31.022
<i>President Roosevelt signs
the Neutrality Law.</i>

31:31.024 --> 31:33.855
<i>And then captive coal mine
strike ties up production.</i>

31:33.857 --> 31:36.656
<i>And Congress prepares
anti-strike legislation.</i>

31:36.658 --> 31:38.490
<i>And in France,
the Germans advanced</i>

31:38.492 --> 31:40.422
<i>along the Saint-Michel salient</i>

31:40.424 --> 31:43.255
<i>taking in the town
of Saint Ramelle and Toulon.</i>

31:43.257 --> 31:45.088
<i>On the southern front</i>

31:45.090 --> 31:47.522
<i>allied advances
continued in Sicily.</i>

31:49.559 --> 31:51.822
Great report on
the Serbian border unit.

31:51.824 --> 31:52.888
Thank you.

31:52.890 --> 31:54.989
[sighs]
I'm going crazy.

31:54.991 --> 31:57.321
I am not made
for desk work, alright?

31:57.323 --> 31:59.254
You got to get me
out onto the field.

31:59.256 --> 32:01.788
- You're useful here.
- Well, I hate it, alright?

32:01.790 --> 32:04.088
I'm used to being
on a ball field all day.

32:04.090 --> 32:06.222
If I stay cooped up in here,
I'm going to kill somebody.

32:06.224 --> 32:08.422
Maybe myself.

32:08.424 --> 32:11.355
[instrumental music]

32:40.124 --> 32:41.356
Oh!

32:42.756 --> 32:43.889
- Oh!
- Oh!

32:45.157 --> 32:46.423
Mr. Berg!

32:52.189 --> 32:54.155
Yeah?

32:54.157 --> 32:55.756
Someone chasing you?

32:56.757 --> 32:58.553
I don't know.

32:58.555 --> 33:00.288
Well, it's good
that you're here.

33:00.290 --> 33:01.821
Come with me.

33:03.990 --> 33:05.254
Where are we going?

33:05.256 --> 33:07.120
Be careful
what you wish for, Berg.

33:07.122 --> 33:08.189
Because you just might get it?

33:08.191 --> 33:09.656
Because it could get you
killed.

33:15.155 --> 33:16.388
Gentlemen.

33:17.490 --> 33:18.856
Moe Berg. Bob Furman.

33:20.155 --> 33:21.520
Hi, nice to meet you.

33:21.522 --> 33:23.587
This is Professor
Sam Goudsmit.

33:23.589 --> 33:24.854
[speaking in foreign language]

33:24.856 --> 33:27.020
If you would.

33:27.022 --> 33:29.954
Bob, Moe, Sam.

33:40.056 --> 33:41.956
We have something for you.

33:43.789 --> 33:45.986
Since this war began..

33:45.988 --> 33:48.954
...we've been engaged
in a massive research

33:48.956 --> 33:51.888
and development program,
called the Manhattan Project.

33:52.856 --> 33:54.286
The purpose of which

33:54.288 --> 33:56.454
is the creation
of a fission bomb.

33:57.657 --> 33:59.786
Now, if initial calculations
are correct

33:59.788 --> 34:03.120
one bomb would be enough
to wipe out an entire city.

34:03.122 --> 34:06.521
The war could be decided
in a day.

34:06.523 --> 34:07.954
We have reason to believe

34:07.956 --> 34:10.389
the Germans are also working
on such a bomb.

34:11.521 --> 34:12.388
Sam.

34:12.389 --> 34:13.887
The scientist leading

34:13.889 --> 34:16.353
the atomic fission program

34:16.356 --> 34:17.920
is Werner Heisenberg.

34:19.989 --> 34:23.954
So, we must get to him

34:23.956 --> 34:26.022
and find out how close
the Germans are to a bomb.

34:27.955 --> 34:30.585
Now, he has left Berlin.

34:30.588 --> 34:33.089
And we don't know where
he is or what he is doing.

34:33.091 --> 34:35.054
But, uh, he has remained
in contact

34:35.056 --> 34:36.619
with an Italian physicist

34:36.621 --> 34:40.320
with whom I worked,
uh, Eduardo Amaldi.

34:40.322 --> 34:43.054
So we'd start in Italy,
the three of us.

34:44.389 --> 34:47.319
Sam for the physics,
me, military

34:47.321 --> 34:49.054
and you, OSS.

34:50.688 --> 34:53.420
- Where in Italy?
- Rome.

34:53.422 --> 34:55.088
Our fifth army is
moving north.

34:55.090 --> 34:58.453
They should take the city
in a week or two.

34:58.455 --> 35:01.518
We'll go in, find the
physicist and interrogate him.

35:01.520 --> 35:04.953
Uh, interview him, please.

35:04.955 --> 35:06.053
Amaldi is my friend.

35:06.055 --> 35:09.220
Uh, if the Italian physicist
has any value

35:09.222 --> 35:12.222
won't the Germans take him when
they pull out, or kill him?

35:12.224 --> 35:15.121
Well, that's why we'd actually
go in with the Fifth Army

35:15.123 --> 35:16.554
to prevent that from
happening.

35:19.489 --> 35:21.054
It's not desk work.

35:21.056 --> 35:22.154
No, it's not.

35:23.390 --> 35:25.519
Could be fun.

35:25.521 --> 35:28.787
Ah, an athlete's
uncomplicated hubris.

35:30.487 --> 35:33.320
I do not speak of fun,
Mr. Berg.

35:33.322 --> 35:34.654
Figure of speech.

35:34.656 --> 35:36.587
[instrumental music]

35:36.589 --> 35:38.285
<i>If the enemy intercepts
your communication</i>

35:38.287 --> 35:40.655
<i>they can easily discern
what you have written there</i>

35:40.657 --> 35:42.953
simply by holding
the paper over a flame

35:42.955 --> 35:44.687
or treating it
with a reactive chemical

35:44.689 --> 35:46.820
<i>such as sodium carbonate.</i>

35:50.054 --> 35:51.487
[grunting]

35:52.987 --> 35:54.654
The German MP 40.

35:54.656 --> 35:57.355
Very effective weapon
for close combat.

35:57.357 --> 35:59.921
Never hold the gun
by the clip when firing

35:59.923 --> 36:02.487
<i>as that can cause
the gun to jam.</i>

36:02.489 --> 36:05.052
<i>Cameras used by both
civilians and military</i>

36:05.054 --> 36:07.253
<i>depending on the situations..</i>

36:07.255 --> 36:08.987
[panting]

36:12.055 --> 36:14.055
[instrumental music]

36:17.822 --> 36:20.785
♪ Don't wake too soon ♪

36:20.787 --> 36:22.387
♪ Don't look too long ♪

36:22.389 --> 36:26.984
♪ Don't peer
beyond the moonlight ♪

36:26.986 --> 36:31.518
♪ Cling to me sing to me.. ♪♪

36:31.520 --> 36:32.886
How's work?

36:33.522 --> 36:34.986
It's just work.

36:36.155 --> 36:38.088
And when do you go back to DC?

36:38.755 --> 36:41.555
I, uh, I'm not going to DC.

36:42.321 --> 36:43.819
Not for a while.

36:43.821 --> 36:45.953
Well, how long do I have you?

36:45.955 --> 36:46.953
Hm?

36:48.987 --> 36:50.220
Till tomorrow.

36:53.888 --> 36:56.122
- Why am I not surprised?
- I'm sorry, Stell.

36:57.356 --> 36:58.587
I'm..

37:01.253 --> 37:02.786
...going overseas.

37:06.287 --> 37:08.486
You brought me here
to say goodbye?

37:08.488 --> 37:10.221
- I'll be back.
- Who knows?

37:16.355 --> 37:18.955
Y... you know that I love you.

37:21.389 --> 37:22.652
Simple yes or no.

37:22.654 --> 37:25.319
D... do you know
that I love you?

37:25.321 --> 37:27.054
[instrumental music]

37:39.520 --> 37:41.654
[engine revving]

38:09.987 --> 38:12.087
I really wanted us
to be perfect.

38:12.953 --> 38:14.119
That's all.

38:15.455 --> 38:16.753
We are.

38:19.019 --> 38:20.118
Liar.

38:25.053 --> 38:26.786
[instrumental music]

38:36.053 --> 38:37.685
Difficult?

38:37.687 --> 38:40.819
[music continues]

39:00.952 --> 39:03.019
[footsteps approaching]

39:03.021 --> 39:04.287
[knock on door]

39:05.554 --> 39:07.819
- May I?
- Hey. Come in.

39:08.687 --> 39:10.053
[exhales]

39:19.822 --> 39:21.620
Tell me about Heisenberg.

39:24.219 --> 39:26.152
Well, he's a somewhat
complicated man.

39:27.821 --> 39:29.184
Yeah, just before
the war started

39:29.186 --> 39:30.785
uh, we were together
at the conference

39:30.787 --> 39:32.720
at the University of Michigan.

39:33.687 --> 39:36.319
And Furman and I begged him

39:36.321 --> 39:38.217
not to go back to Germany.

39:38.219 --> 39:39.184
- But he went.
- Yeah.

39:39.186 --> 39:42.085
But to save German science
from the Nazis.

39:43.453 --> 39:46.350
And now he's the head
of the atomic bomb program.

39:47.453 --> 39:49.149
Could he build a bomb?

39:49.151 --> 39:51.885
Could he or would he?

39:52.886 --> 39:54.284
Both.

39:54.286 --> 39:55.684
The could of it would require

39:55.686 --> 39:58.418
enormous physical
and financial resources

39:58.420 --> 40:01.650
perhaps more than Germany
has at its disposal.

40:01.652 --> 40:04.917
But with the resources,
he could do it.

40:06.319 --> 40:07.752
Yes.

40:09.220 --> 40:10.851
And the would of it?

40:12.552 --> 40:13.984
I don't know.

40:15.052 --> 40:16.286
I don't know.

40:22.719 --> 40:24.652
So you were friends?

40:24.654 --> 40:26.084
You knew him well?

40:27.619 --> 40:28.818
Yeah.

40:30.220 --> 40:32.153
Do you still
consider him a friend?

40:34.051 --> 40:36.852
You are a Jew, yeah, Mr. Berg?

40:38.620 --> 40:39.853
Jewish.

40:42.120 --> 40:43.984
A... after the Nazis
occupied Holland

40:43.986 --> 40:46.350
my parents were taken
to Auschwitz.

40:46.352 --> 40:50.117
Now, I contacted Heisenberg
and I asked him

40:50.119 --> 40:53.719
I... begged him
to do what he could.

40:55.953 --> 40:57.885
And we haven't spoken since.

40:59.653 --> 41:01.986
I don't know
if they're dead or alive.

41:14.685 --> 41:16.216
<i>Thanks.</i>

41:16.218 --> 41:17.951
[instrumental music]

41:29.919 --> 41:31.817
I'm not comfortable with this.

41:31.819 --> 41:33.317
We'll be alright.

41:33.319 --> 41:35.882
What if there are Germans
waiting for us?

41:35.884 --> 41:38.916
Then we'll probably
get shot and killed.

41:38.918 --> 41:41.515
[sighs] This has all the
variables of a disaster.

41:41.517 --> 41:45.084
Sam, stop your whining.

41:45.086 --> 41:47.351
[grunts]

41:57.452 --> 41:58.517
- Ah-ha.
- Here we are.

41:59.653 --> 42:01.485
Welcome to Italy, sir.

42:06.018 --> 42:07.516
[grunts]

42:07.518 --> 42:09.451
[engine revving]

42:12.517 --> 42:14.017
Be careful!

42:18.418 --> 42:20.018
[kids laughing]

42:38.985 --> 42:41.649
You doing alright?

42:41.651 --> 42:43.449
- You don't look so great.
- Nah..

42:43.451 --> 42:45.217
Quite well, thank you.

42:52.784 --> 42:54.050
Who the hell are you?

42:54.918 --> 42:56.383
[explosions]

42:56.385 --> 42:58.482
- What's up there?
- Goddamn Germans.

42:58.484 --> 43:00.681
Left the rearguard division.

43:00.683 --> 43:02.116
Paying for every inch.

43:03.919 --> 43:06.048
What's the safest way
to Piazza Leone?

43:06.050 --> 43:08.383
Why don't you drive
south 30 miles

43:08.385 --> 43:10.551
find yourself a nice hotel,
wait a week?

43:10.553 --> 43:12.950
We can't wait.

43:12.952 --> 43:14.916
Alright, fine. Your call.

43:14.918 --> 43:17.382
Look, stay on the Via Appia
as long as you can.

43:17.384 --> 43:19.416
Stash your Jeep
when it gets too messy.

43:19.418 --> 43:20.750
But as of this morning
that whole area

43:20.752 --> 43:23.015
was crawling with Krauts.

43:23.017 --> 43:25.582
- And good luck.
- Thanks.

43:25.584 --> 43:27.017
Alright, let them through.

43:27.019 --> 43:28.084
- Yes, sir.
- Yes, sir.

43:28.086 --> 43:31.217
[instrumental music]

43:59.051 --> 44:01.216
Follow me and stay down.

44:01.218 --> 44:02.583
Duck.

44:08.416 --> 44:09.648
[indistinct chatter]

44:09.650 --> 44:11.781
There's still
Krauts everywhere.

44:11.783 --> 44:13.049
Ready? Move out.

44:13.051 --> 44:14.915
Yeah, come on.

44:14.917 --> 44:18.048
[panting]

44:28.118 --> 44:31.049
[music continues]

44:49.085 --> 44:50.549
[metal creaking]

44:52.452 --> 44:54.482
So you're the guys
they told us about.

44:54.484 --> 44:55.749
You guys are crazy.

44:55.751 --> 44:57.249
Yeah.

44:57.251 --> 44:58.516
Alright, let's move out.

44:59.351 --> 45:00.816
Go, go, go.

45:03.184 --> 45:05.549
Look at me. We'll be alright.
Alright?

45:11.051 --> 45:13.183
[panting]

45:15.085 --> 45:16.381
[shouting in foreign language]

45:16.383 --> 45:19.017
[gunshots]

45:21.649 --> 45:23.014
[indistinct shouting]

45:23.016 --> 45:24.281
Get down!

45:24.283 --> 45:25.415
[gunshots]

45:25.417 --> 45:26.650
Get down!

45:28.283 --> 45:29.747
[shouting in foreign language]

45:29.749 --> 45:32.681
[gunshots]

45:35.450 --> 45:37.482
Get ready to run
to that wall.

45:37.484 --> 45:38.648
Wait till I call.

45:38.650 --> 45:40.848
[indistinct chatter]

45:40.850 --> 45:42.315
Okay, go!

45:42.317 --> 45:44.081
[gunshots]

45:44.083 --> 45:45.680
[panting]

45:45.682 --> 45:46.948
[indistinct shouting]

45:46.950 --> 45:49.684
[gunshots]

45:58.250 --> 46:00.748
[indistinct shouting]

46:00.750 --> 46:02.348
[gunshots]

46:02.350 --> 46:05.649
<i>Get down! Get down!</i>

46:05.651 --> 46:08.582
[gun firing]

46:19.216 --> 46:21.316
[indistinct shouting]

46:23.816 --> 46:25.547
[gun firing]

46:29.148 --> 46:31.747
- Grenade!
- <i>Go, go, go!</i>

46:31.749 --> 46:33.915
- <i>Get down!</i>
- Aah!

46:33.917 --> 46:35.114
Go, go, go, go!

46:35.116 --> 46:36.849
[panting]

46:38.718 --> 46:41.581
[gun firing]

46:41.583 --> 46:44.182
[indistinct shouting]

46:45.084 --> 46:46.684
[exhales]

46:48.017 --> 46:49.283
Uh, come on.

46:57.116 --> 47:00.080
[gun firing]

47:00.082 --> 47:01.749
<i>Panzer! Panzer!</i>

47:06.382 --> 47:09.116
[grunting]

47:10.351 --> 47:12.181
- Move out!
- Get up! Move!

47:12.183 --> 47:13.381
- Let's go.
- <i>Whoo!</i>

47:13.383 --> 47:16.115
[indistinct screaming]

47:16.117 --> 47:17.850
Move! Move! Move!

47:26.148 --> 47:27.748
[explosion]

47:30.749 --> 47:32.513
- Aah!
- Move out!

47:32.515 --> 47:34.448
[panting]

47:37.581 --> 47:39.315
[indistinct yelling]

47:43.382 --> 47:45.514
[indistinct chatter]

47:53.382 --> 47:55.213
<i>Roll, roll, roll!</i>

47:55.215 --> 47:57.148
[panting]

48:03.982 --> 48:06.980
No, uh.. Uh, that's Amaldi's.

48:06.982 --> 48:08.248
<i>Upper floor.</i>

48:10.448 --> 48:11.680
Behind me.

48:14.115 --> 48:16.282
[speaking in foreign language]

48:17.949 --> 48:19.715
[gunshots]

48:20.882 --> 48:23.047
[speaking in foreign language]

48:23.049 --> 48:24.848
We got to go.

48:24.850 --> 48:26.782
[gunshots]

48:27.414 --> 48:29.348
- Go, go.
- Yeah?

48:29.350 --> 48:31.113
- Wait, get back.
- Yeah!

48:31.115 --> 48:33.714
[gunshots]

48:37.049 --> 48:38.914
Let's go.

48:38.916 --> 48:40.849
[panting]

48:49.248 --> 48:51.382
[gunshots]

48:52.282 --> 48:54.414
[panting]

48:58.649 --> 49:01.279
[gunshots]

49:01.281 --> 49:02.647
Go! Go!

49:02.649 --> 49:04.515
[gunshots]

49:06.947 --> 49:09.613
[speaking in foreign language]

49:09.615 --> 49:11.548
[panting]

49:14.248 --> 49:15.679
[gun clicks]

49:15.681 --> 49:17.214
[grunts]
Shit.

49:17.216 --> 49:18.949
[gunshots]

49:20.882 --> 49:23.180
[panting]

49:23.182 --> 49:24.914
[speaking in foreign language]

49:26.148 --> 49:27.381
<i>Gracias.</i>

49:28.717 --> 49:30.212
Halt!

49:30.214 --> 49:31.947
[grunts]

49:38.282 --> 49:41.146
[breathing heavily]

49:41.148 --> 49:42.414
You okay?

49:43.282 --> 49:44.713
You're good, come on.

49:47.081 --> 49:48.681
Hold position!

49:51.815 --> 49:54.511
It looks like we've got
the city up past the Vatican.

49:54.513 --> 49:57.044
The Germans have pulled back
their rearguard.

49:57.046 --> 49:59.780
[speaking in foreign language]

50:10.513 --> 50:12.312
- Alright, alright.
- Thank you.

50:12.314 --> 50:13.513
<i>You'll be fine, buddy.</i>

50:13.515 --> 50:15.013
[speaking in foreign language]

50:15.015 --> 50:17.945
[speaking in foreign language]

50:42.047 --> 50:44.979
[speaking in foreign language]

51:01.549 --> 51:02.813
[clears throat]

51:02.815 --> 51:05.879
[speaking in foreign language]

51:22.747 --> 51:25.678
[speaking in foreign language]

51:30.847 --> 51:32.313
[chuckles]

51:32.315 --> 51:35.048
[speaking in foreign language]

51:56.413 --> 51:59.147
[speaking in foreign language]

52:14.781 --> 52:16.478
They don't have it,
they're still building

52:16.480 --> 52:19.711
carbon molding frames
instead of shaped housings.

52:19.713 --> 52:22.245
He's writing about heavy water
absorption rates.

52:22.247 --> 52:23.745
This letter,
he asks Amaldi for help

52:23.747 --> 52:25.744
with casement tolerances.

52:25.746 --> 52:27.179
Here, he says
he's doing

52:27.181 --> 52:29.844
large-structure analysis.

52:29.846 --> 52:32.713
Everything points to a reactor
instead of a bomb.

52:32.715 --> 52:35.410
How do we know
these documents aren't decoys?

52:35.412 --> 52:37.111
Plants?

52:37.113 --> 52:39.346
Uh, they're letters.

52:39.348 --> 52:42.077
Personal letters.
These men are friends.

52:42.079 --> 52:45.679
The physics is, uh,
intertwined with the intimacy.

52:45.681 --> 52:48.746
Hmm, we have to be sure.

52:48.748 --> 52:51.578
Then have the British review it.
They are physicists.

52:51.580 --> 52:53.143
They will confirm what I say.

52:53.145 --> 52:54.877
Alright.

52:54.879 --> 52:57.343
We'll have
the Brits weigh in.

52:57.345 --> 52:59.010
Donovan will be here soon.

52:59.012 --> 53:00.510
I'm kicking this upstairs.

53:00.512 --> 53:03.578
[revving]

53:06.279 --> 53:09.013
[instrumental music]

53:21.478 --> 53:23.043
- Mr. Berg.
- Hello, sir.

53:23.045 --> 53:24.712
- How's it been going?
- Going well. Yes, sir.

53:24.714 --> 53:26.846
[indistinct chatter]

53:30.747 --> 53:32.745
And the industrial complex
at Hechingen

53:32.747 --> 53:34.678
has only a containment vessel

53:34.680 --> 53:36.011
and a cycle stack

53:36.013 --> 53:38.610
both signs of a nascent
reactor facility.

53:38.612 --> 53:41.179
And the uranium
separation facility?

53:41.181 --> 53:42.576
Consensus in London is

53:42.578 --> 53:44.712
that's just a carbon separator
of some sort.

53:44.714 --> 53:46.377
An attempt at shale
extraction.

53:46.379 --> 53:48.142
- <i>Coal?</i>
- Apparently so.

53:48.144 --> 53:49.678
I concur.

53:49.680 --> 53:51.645
So, where does this leave us?

53:51.647 --> 53:53.345
London is certain.

53:53.347 --> 53:54.976
No German bomb.

53:54.978 --> 53:57.811
<i>Degree of certainty?</i>

53:57.813 --> 53:59.943
There's no such thing
as a degree of certainty.

53:59.945 --> 54:03.210
I mean, something is
either certain or it is not.

54:03.212 --> 54:04.611
<i>Hmm.</i>

54:04.613 --> 54:07.277
<i>Thank you, gentlemen.</i>

54:07.279 --> 54:09.711
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

54:15.146 --> 54:17.676
[door opens]

54:17.678 --> 54:19.044
So, what are the alternatives?

54:21.080 --> 54:23.513
Bombing Hechingen
is unlikely to be effective.

54:24.845 --> 54:26.945
If they are developing a bomb

54:26.947 --> 54:29.044
the work, the materials
will be spread out

54:29.046 --> 54:31.077
at facilities
and other factories.

54:31.079 --> 54:34.777
So our British allies
tell us 100% no German bomb.

54:34.779 --> 54:36.877
My people tell me
a 20% possibility.

54:36.879 --> 54:38.875
More likely ten or
five percent.

54:38.877 --> 54:40.677
- Perhaps less.
- <i>But not zero.</i>

54:40.679 --> 54:42.843
It's Probability 101.

54:42.845 --> 54:45.743
You multiply the likelihood of
the event by the consequence.

54:45.745 --> 54:46.812
Five percent chance you're

54:46.814 --> 54:48.444
going to stub your toe in the
dark

54:48.446 --> 54:49.844
you take the chance,
walk to the bathroom

54:49.846 --> 54:51.943
without turning on the lights
and waking your wife.

54:51.945 --> 54:55.775
A five percent chance of losingthe
war to a weapon like this

54:55.777 --> 54:58.542
you do what has to be done.

54:58.544 --> 55:00.845
Which is?

55:00.847 --> 55:02.979
We kill Heisenberg.

55:07.645 --> 55:09.578
What if he's on our side?

55:11.246 --> 55:14.877
Why is it that the Germans
haven't developed a bomb?

55:14.879 --> 55:16.310
Heisenberg has a team of
at least

55:16.312 --> 55:18.542
a dozen capable physicists.

55:18.544 --> 55:19.910
What have they been doing?

55:19.912 --> 55:22.843
What are you saying?
He's dragging his feet?

55:22.845 --> 55:24.543
Intentionally slowing
the program?

55:24.545 --> 55:26.545
I do not think
that Werner Heisenberg

55:26.547 --> 55:29.475
would want to be remembered
as a traitor.

55:29.477 --> 55:31.477
The man who lost the war
for Germany?

55:31.479 --> 55:33.109
We are not absolutely
sure of that

55:33.111 --> 55:34.777
nor do we have
any actual evidence

55:34.779 --> 55:36.076
that he's secretly
working for us.

55:36.078 --> 55:38.177
There are millions of lives
at stake.

55:38.179 --> 55:39.677
I'm sorry.

55:41.778 --> 55:43.910
[indistinct chatter]

55:46.245 --> 55:48.344
<i>Werner Heisenberg..</i>

55:48.346 --> 55:51.112
<i>Pioneer in the study
of subatomic particles.</i>

55:52.811 --> 55:55.642
<i>Winner of the 1932
Nobel Prize in physics</i>

55:55.644 --> 55:58.278
<i>for the creation
of quantum mechanics.</i>

56:02.511 --> 56:04.208
<i>Equation 56 is known</i>

56:04.210 --> 56:07.075
<i>as Heisenberg's principle
of uncertainty.</i>

56:08.810 --> 56:10.910
<i>The principle shows
that one can never observe</i>

56:10.912 --> 56:13.444
<i>both the position
and velocity of a particle</i>

56:13.446 --> 56:15.279
<i>at the same time.</i>

56:16.878 --> 56:18.775
<i>One cannot be certain
where something is</i>

56:18.777 --> 56:20.710
<i>and where it is going.</i>

56:23.945 --> 56:27.410
<i>And thus, Heisenberg proves
that no one knows anything.</i>

56:29.745 --> 56:32.178
<i>We live in eternal
uncertainty.</i>

56:35.378 --> 56:37.344
<i>A man after my own heart.</i>

56:51.311 --> 56:54.409
You like libraries.

56:54.411 --> 56:55.776
Why?

56:56.810 --> 57:00.042
Here is a belongingness

57:00.044 --> 57:02.076
I find in few other places.

57:03.844 --> 57:06.108
On a ball field?

57:06.110 --> 57:07.309
There too.

57:08.845 --> 57:11.108
That's gone now.

57:11.110 --> 57:12.641
I have to ask you
a question

57:12.643 --> 57:14.310
and I need a real answer.

57:15.911 --> 57:18.608
If it comes down to it

57:18.610 --> 57:20.910
are you going to be able
to kill him?

57:24.111 --> 57:25.210
Yes.

57:28.378 --> 57:31.308
[indistinct chatter]

57:32.511 --> 57:34.043
<i>There you go.</i>

57:38.845 --> 57:40.377
You wanna play?

57:41.510 --> 57:44.244
Huh, good.
You, uh, got a choice?

57:46.677 --> 57:48.943
- Catcher?
- It's all yours.

57:49.844 --> 57:52.975
[instrumental music]

58:00.811 --> 58:02.543
[indistinct chatter]

58:06.744 --> 58:09.342
Oh, shit.

58:09.344 --> 58:11.944
- The guy's a pro.
- Yeah.

58:18.376 --> 58:19.807
[gunshot]

58:26.543 --> 58:27.842
I know who that is.

58:29.279 --> 58:30.511
That's Moe Berg.

58:32.843 --> 58:34.242
[gunshot]

58:36.811 --> 58:39.609
<i>Home plate, home plate!</i>

58:39.611 --> 58:41.343
[indistinct chatter]

58:42.710 --> 58:44.442
- Yes!
- Alright.

58:47.310 --> 58:49.542
[gunshot]

58:52.642 --> 58:55.475
Uh-oh. Move back, move back.

58:55.477 --> 58:58.307
Don't worry,
245 lifetime.

58:58.309 --> 59:01.308
Yeah, yeah, just don't hit it
down my throat, okay?

59:05.042 --> 59:06.408
<i>Oh!</i>

59:08.712 --> 59:10.241
[applauding]

59:10.243 --> 59:11.942
<i>That's a hit!</i>

59:11.944 --> 59:14.941
[indistinct chatter]

59:19.510 --> 59:21.274
Jesus Christ!

59:21.276 --> 59:22.875
Moe Berg, thanks.

59:22.877 --> 59:25.810
Oh, no. Don't thank me.
Thank you.

59:25.812 --> 59:28.076
Hey, do you mind,
uh, signing the ball?

59:28.078 --> 59:30.274
- Yeah, sure.
- Thanks a lot, Moe.

59:30.276 --> 59:32.041
You know, I saw you
a dozen times at Fenway.

59:32.043 --> 59:35.541
- You were great.
- Me? Great? When?

59:35.543 --> 59:37.772
Uh, well, I saw you.

59:37.774 --> 59:41.074
- Yeah.
- Thanks.

59:41.076 --> 59:44.008
[indistinct chatter]

59:48.378 --> 59:50.311
[gunshot]

59:56.043 --> 59:59.509
Zurich. It's a short train
journey from Hechingen.

59:59.511 --> 01:00:02.674
A break from the grim
atmosphere of Germany.

01:00:02.676 --> 01:00:04.207
He will be tempted.

01:00:04.209 --> 01:00:06.008
And I know someone in Zurich.

01:00:06.010 --> 01:00:07.841
Paul Scherrer.

01:00:07.843 --> 01:00:09.239
He and Heisenberg
are good friends.

01:00:09.241 --> 01:00:12.106
- They play chess by mail.
- He's anti-Nazi.

01:00:12.108 --> 01:00:14.840
Exactly, but he and Heisenberg
are still close.

01:00:14.842 --> 01:00:16.739
And he gonna help us
lure Heisenberg to Zurich?

01:00:16.741 --> 01:00:19.408
Such a word, "Lure."

01:00:19.410 --> 01:00:23.040
Heisenberg has been there
twice since the war started.

01:00:23.042 --> 01:00:26.807
We simply have Scherrer invite
him to deliver a lecture.

01:00:26.809 --> 01:00:28.708
Can Scherrer be persuaded
to work with us?

01:00:28.710 --> 01:00:31.376
Yes. Scherrer will arrange it.

01:00:37.109 --> 01:00:39.974
And so the madness
becomes real.

01:00:41.709 --> 01:00:43.640
We have to kill
Werner Heisenberg

01:00:43.642 --> 01:00:45.807
and I am to be a part of it.

01:00:45.809 --> 01:00:47.807
No one wants
to kill Heisenberg.

01:00:47.809 --> 01:00:49.373
Yeah? Then kidnap him.

01:00:49.375 --> 01:00:51.841
Send in spies to Germany
and kidnap him.

01:00:51.843 --> 01:00:54.275
You've read too many
spy novels.

01:00:54.277 --> 01:00:57.073
I've never read a spy novel.

01:00:57.075 --> 01:00:58.874
It's not that easy
to kidnap somebody.

01:00:58.876 --> 01:01:00.807
Ah.

01:01:00.809 --> 01:01:02.642
Yeah,
you mean killing is easier.

01:01:05.875 --> 01:01:07.609
My God.

01:01:12.508 --> 01:01:14.441
[engine revving]

01:01:16.408 --> 01:01:19.407
You'll have about 30 miles
on foot to the Swiss border.

01:01:21.208 --> 01:01:22.541
I'd hold on to your gun.

01:01:22.543 --> 01:01:25.606
I have some reservations
about your guides.

01:01:25.608 --> 01:01:27.974
Reservations?
Like what?

01:01:27.976 --> 01:01:30.672
Reservations like
they might kill you.

01:01:30.674 --> 01:01:33.408
You might have cared
to add that to the report.

01:01:40.608 --> 01:01:42.375
There's your guides.

01:01:43.476 --> 01:01:44.973
[sighs]

01:01:44.975 --> 01:01:46.274
Wish me luck.

01:01:46.276 --> 01:01:48.341
I don't wanna hear you
depending on luck.

01:01:49.908 --> 01:01:51.474
Figure of speech.

01:01:54.608 --> 01:01:56.006
Thank you, Sam.

01:01:56.008 --> 01:01:57.974
Thank you, Moe.

01:02:05.343 --> 01:02:08.273
[dramatic music]

01:02:10.441 --> 01:02:13.373
[engine revving]

01:02:20.475 --> 01:02:23.209
[instrumental music]

01:02:29.709 --> 01:02:32.639
[panting]

01:02:37.873 --> 01:02:39.473
[grunts]

01:02:45.776 --> 01:02:48.440
[panting]

01:02:48.442 --> 01:02:49.639
Now we rest.

01:02:49.641 --> 01:02:50.706
[groans]

01:02:50.708 --> 01:02:53.240
<i>Riposo.</i>

01:02:53.242 --> 01:02:54.508
No.

01:02:55.407 --> 01:02:58.338
[speaking in foreign language]

01:03:02.241 --> 01:03:05.106
[speaking in foreign language]

01:03:21.909 --> 01:03:24.642
[speaking in foreign language]

01:03:30.741 --> 01:03:33.673
[footsteps]

01:03:40.740 --> 01:03:43.672
[speaking in foreign language]

01:03:51.107 --> 01:03:53.840
[speaking in foreign language]

01:04:05.741 --> 01:04:07.741
[speaking in foreign language]

01:04:21.208 --> 01:04:24.138
- Hi, are you okay?
- Yeah.

01:04:27.008 --> 01:04:29.506
Who came up
with that sheep nonsense?

01:04:29.508 --> 01:04:32.439
- I don't know.
- I felt like an idiot.

01:04:32.441 --> 01:04:33.606
So did I.

01:04:40.473 --> 01:04:41.640
Switzerland?

01:04:43.107 --> 01:04:45.139
Yes.

01:04:45.141 --> 01:04:46.607
Let's go.

01:04:47.641 --> 01:04:50.572
[brakes squeaking]

01:05:00.406 --> 01:05:03.538
[instrumental music]

01:05:14.840 --> 01:05:16.840
That's Heisenberg.

01:05:20.374 --> 01:05:21.870
It's good to see you..

01:05:21.872 --> 01:05:23.740
<i>And that's Professor Scherrer.</i>

01:05:24.973 --> 01:05:27.471
Scherrer looks way to nervous.

01:05:27.473 --> 01:05:29.605
I guess this isn't his thing.

01:05:30.574 --> 01:05:31.740
What?

01:05:33.007 --> 01:05:34.505
Treachery.

01:05:37.307 --> 01:05:40.038
[indistinct chatter]

01:05:40.040 --> 01:05:41.906
[knock on door]

01:05:51.041 --> 01:05:53.605
- <i>Professor Scherrer.</i>
- Mr. Aziz, please come in.

01:05:53.607 --> 01:05:54.739
Thank you.

01:05:58.573 --> 01:06:00.836
My name's Berg.

01:06:00.838 --> 01:06:03.937
Oh, so who is Mr. Aziz?

01:06:03.939 --> 01:06:05.305
A cover name.

01:06:05.307 --> 01:06:07.338
I prefer you and I
tell each other the truth.

01:06:07.340 --> 01:06:09.471
I'm Morris Berg.

01:06:09.473 --> 01:06:11.237
Oh.

01:06:11.239 --> 01:06:14.538
Sam Goudsmit
sends his regards.

01:06:14.540 --> 01:06:15.505
Ah, well.

01:06:15.507 --> 01:06:18.804
I was hoping
he would come here personally.

01:06:19.907 --> 01:06:21.805
Please, please sit down.

01:06:21.807 --> 01:06:24.971
Well, he, uh..

01:06:24.973 --> 01:06:26.572
He sent you something.

01:06:32.640 --> 01:06:33.739
Heavy water.

01:06:35.205 --> 01:06:37.338
Nordstemmen impurity.

01:06:41.306 --> 01:06:44.472
Oh, thank you so much.

01:06:44.474 --> 01:06:46.470
No, you don't know
how much I appreciate this.

01:06:46.472 --> 01:06:48.370
Thank you so much.

01:06:48.372 --> 01:06:50.904
You don't worry
I give this to the Germans?

01:06:52.038 --> 01:06:54.339
We trust you, professor.

01:06:57.371 --> 01:06:59.304
I may be mistaken, but..

01:07:01.173 --> 01:07:02.769
I don't think
Professor Heisenberg

01:07:02.771 --> 01:07:06.203
will reveal anything
in his lecture.

01:07:06.205 --> 01:07:08.337
Hmm.

01:07:08.339 --> 01:07:11.837
Well, then perhaps I could
speak with him privately.

01:07:13.006 --> 01:07:14.970
Are you hoping he'll defect?

01:07:14.972 --> 01:07:17.171
Yes, I am.

01:07:17.173 --> 01:07:19.303
[laughs]

01:07:19.305 --> 01:07:20.770
Good luck.

01:07:23.172 --> 01:07:25.906
[instrumental music]

01:07:41.040 --> 01:07:42.605
Excuse me one moment.

01:07:54.172 --> 01:07:55.704
[sighs]

01:07:59.306 --> 01:08:01.171
[gun clicking]

01:08:08.739 --> 01:08:10.672
[flushes toilet]

01:08:37.005 --> 01:08:39.935
[speaking in foreign language]

01:09:10.006 --> 01:09:11.835
Got to listen carefully.

01:09:11.837 --> 01:09:13.368
There may be one moment
that tells you

01:09:13.371 --> 01:09:16.437
whether the Germans have a
chance at a fission bomb or not.

01:09:16.439 --> 01:09:20.069
One moment, and you'll learn
all you need to know.

01:09:20.071 --> 01:09:21.870
You understand me, catcher?

01:09:23.537 --> 01:09:24.737
I understand you.

01:09:24.738 --> 01:09:27.868
[speaking in foreign language]

01:09:33.705 --> 01:09:35.935
<i>In that moment,
without hesitation</i>

01:09:35.938 --> 01:09:38.801
you will shoot Heisenberg
dead on the spot.

01:09:39.805 --> 01:09:42.938
[speaking in foreign language]

01:09:54.136 --> 01:09:57.068
[speaking in foreign language]

01:10:16.737 --> 01:10:19.170
Did he accept
your dinner invitation?

01:10:19.172 --> 01:10:21.870
I prevailed upon our
friendship. He'll be there.

01:10:21.872 --> 01:10:23.236
Good.

01:10:23.238 --> 01:10:26.201
What if he doesn't tell you
what you want to know?

01:10:26.203 --> 01:10:28.636
I'll do my best
to be persuasive.

01:10:28.638 --> 01:10:31.735
There's always a possibility
that you will learn nothing.

01:10:31.737 --> 01:10:33.868
But at least
we will have tried.

01:10:33.870 --> 01:10:35.135
Mr. Berg..

01:10:37.437 --> 01:10:39.934
Is there something
you're not telling me?

01:10:39.936 --> 01:10:42.535
No.

01:10:42.537 --> 01:10:45.104
Do you plan to kill
Professor Heisenberg?

01:10:46.672 --> 01:10:50.170
I have no intention
whatsoever.

01:10:50.172 --> 01:10:51.804
One last thing.

01:11:00.403 --> 01:11:04.169
Heisenberg will have undercover
Gestapo agents watching him

01:11:04.171 --> 01:11:06.738
and you can't allow yourself
to be captured.

01:11:15.304 --> 01:11:18.536
I don't know what God
you believe in, Berg, if any.

01:11:20.738 --> 01:11:23.570
But I'll be asking mine
to keep an eye on you.

01:11:38.336 --> 01:11:41.069
<i>[choir chanting]</i>

01:12:05.471 --> 01:12:08.204
<i>[singing in foreign language]</i>

01:12:38.503 --> 01:12:41.237
[singing continues]

01:12:53.870 --> 01:12:56.800
[indistinct chatter]

01:13:03.936 --> 01:13:06.667
Your call is being
connected, sir.

01:13:06.669 --> 01:13:08.669
<i>Let me know
if there's a problem.</i>

01:13:22.501 --> 01:13:24.234
[telephone ringing]

01:13:25.669 --> 01:13:27.001
Hello?

01:13:29.536 --> 01:13:31.035
Hello?

01:13:34.102 --> 01:13:35.334
<i>Hello?</i>

01:13:37.768 --> 01:13:39.701
Hi, Estella.

01:13:43.070 --> 01:13:45.002
<i>Morris?</i>

01:13:48.636 --> 01:13:50.369
<i>Are you alright?</i>

01:13:53.235 --> 01:13:54.969
I am.

01:13:56.735 --> 01:13:58.301
<i>Where are you?</i>

01:13:59.835 --> 01:14:01.835
Uh, I can't say.

01:14:02.803 --> 01:14:04.535
And I don't have much time.

01:14:05.969 --> 01:14:08.235
But I wanted to call and..

01:14:11.436 --> 01:14:13.435
I wanted to hear your voice.

01:14:19.535 --> 01:14:21.269
I'm here, Moe.

01:14:31.868 --> 01:14:34.002
I have to go.

01:14:36.803 --> 01:14:38.935
I love you.

01:14:56.967 --> 01:14:59.899
[instrumental music]

01:15:22.468 --> 01:15:25.067
[indistinct chatter]

01:15:25.069 --> 01:15:27.167
[speaking in foreign language]

01:15:27.169 --> 01:15:28.267
Thank you.

01:15:31.168 --> 01:15:32.434
[speaking in foreign language]

01:15:51.170 --> 01:15:54.300
[speaking in foreign language]

01:15:58.102 --> 01:16:01.299
[speaking in foreign language]

01:16:16.635 --> 01:16:19.369
[speaking in foreign language]

01:16:29.867 --> 01:16:32.601
[speaking in foreign language]

01:16:58.134 --> 01:17:01.333
[speaking in foreign language]

01:17:08.834 --> 01:17:10.567
[indistinct chatter]

01:17:13.101 --> 01:17:15.166
Who is that, Paul?

01:17:15.168 --> 01:17:16.965
I saw him at the lecture.
What's he doing here?

01:17:16.967 --> 01:17:19.299
Yeah,
he's a good friend of mine.

01:17:19.301 --> 01:17:22.130
I think you'll find him
very engaging.

01:17:22.132 --> 01:17:24.499
You know he carries a gun.

01:17:24.501 --> 01:17:26.701
Yeah.
No need to worry.

01:17:26.703 --> 01:17:28.434
Let's eat.

01:17:36.067 --> 01:17:39.198
[indistinct chatter]

01:17:48.401 --> 01:17:52.532
I just don't understand how you
could have stayed in Germany.

01:17:52.534 --> 01:17:55.433
Oh, please, no politics.

01:17:55.435 --> 01:17:56.532
No war.

01:17:56.534 --> 01:17:59.066
There is a war,
whether you like it or not.

01:17:59.068 --> 01:18:01.330
What are you suggesting?
I like the war?

01:18:01.332 --> 01:18:04.031
I am suggesting that unlike
many of your colleagues

01:18:04.033 --> 01:18:07.130
you elected to stay
in Nazi Germany.

01:18:07.132 --> 01:18:11.432
I elected to stay in Germany,
which happens to be Nazi.

01:18:11.434 --> 01:18:14.732
Do I hear politics
from that end of the table?

01:18:14.734 --> 01:18:17.032
One hears what one
wishes to hear.

01:18:17.034 --> 01:18:19.064
Please, we are all friends.

01:18:19.066 --> 01:18:22.032
Let's talk about old times,
or better times to come.

01:18:22.034 --> 01:18:23.665
Yes, please.

01:18:29.168 --> 01:18:32.099
[speaking in foreign language]

01:18:56.133 --> 01:18:59.065
[speaking in foreign language]

01:19:10.033 --> 01:19:12.766
[speaking in foreign language]

01:19:14.832 --> 01:19:16.764
Aziz?

01:19:16.766 --> 01:19:18.300
Aziz.

01:19:19.234 --> 01:19:21.400
[speaking in foreign language]

01:19:24.099 --> 01:19:27.963
I understand we have a
bad weather tomorrow.

01:19:27.965 --> 01:19:29.531
Rain.

01:19:35.298 --> 01:19:37.996
There is no avoiding
political matters.

01:19:37.998 --> 01:19:39.398
We can try.

01:19:39.400 --> 01:19:40.698
Is that what you've been doing

01:19:40.700 --> 01:19:43.363
as the head of
the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute

01:19:43.365 --> 01:19:45.130
<i>and the Heereswaffenamt?</i>

01:19:45.132 --> 01:19:47.865
I beg of you, we are completely
separate from politics.

01:19:47.867 --> 01:19:49.130
[scoffs]
Oh, I forgot.

01:19:49.132 --> 01:19:51.197
The citizens
of the world, yes?

01:19:51.199 --> 01:19:54.196
Once, and hopefully again
someday.

01:19:54.198 --> 01:19:57.065
<i>Tell that to the Poles,
and the Danes</i>

01:19:57.067 --> 01:19:58.498
the Belgians, the Jews.

01:19:58.500 --> 01:20:01.963
Please,
I'm not a military man.

01:20:01.965 --> 01:20:03.097
We don't know
what sort of man you are.

01:20:03.099 --> 01:20:04.597
Yes, we do.

01:20:04.599 --> 01:20:06.596
He's the kind of man
who is helping the Nazis

01:20:06.598 --> 01:20:07.898
fight their war.

01:20:07.900 --> 01:20:09.665
Building Hitler's super
weapon.

01:20:11.932 --> 01:20:14.734
See?
He doesn't even deny it.

01:20:17.298 --> 01:20:20.031
<i>I feel the war
will be over soon.</i>

01:20:20.033 --> 01:20:21.497
<i>Maybe.</i>

01:20:21.499 --> 01:20:24.864
- And Germany will lose.
- Whatever you say.

01:20:24.866 --> 01:20:26.130
[scoff]

01:20:26.132 --> 01:20:27.565
You disgust me.

01:20:27.567 --> 01:20:30.065
Please, please, please.

01:20:30.067 --> 01:20:32.396
Professor Heisenberg
is my guest.

01:20:32.398 --> 01:20:35.931
Well, then the two of you can
lament Germany's loss together.

01:20:35.933 --> 01:20:37.232
Ugh!

01:20:38.800 --> 01:20:40.463
Please forgive me.

01:20:40.465 --> 01:20:43.397
[speaking in foreign language]

01:20:44.666 --> 01:20:47.097
Werner, please stay.

01:20:47.099 --> 01:20:49.531
I really must go.
I've endured enough of this.

01:20:51.732 --> 01:20:53.332
[door shuts]

01:20:55.066 --> 01:20:57.798
[speaking in foreign language]

01:21:13.098 --> 01:21:14.530
[door shuts]

01:21:18.166 --> 01:21:20.899
[dramatic music]

01:21:40.266 --> 01:21:41.898
[gun clicks]

01:21:46.133 --> 01:21:47.465
[sighs]

01:21:52.998 --> 01:21:55.732
[instrumental music]

01:22:25.465 --> 01:22:27.432
